Timestamp isn't saved until a record is saved in the CSV. Because trying to get the real time at camera capture would be getting the real time like 4 times a second. 

Script the loop makes a decision about whether to do an occupancy check or separately an enter/exit check based on the number of seconds elapsed since the last check. This number of seconds can be configured in the global variables. We're doing it this way even though what we ultimately want is the wall clock time because if we're capturing something every second, even though FPS might be 4 times a second or whatever, we don't really want occupancy every millisecond. We just want enter/exit every second, occupancy once a minute or so, or every 30 seconds. To take even occupancy, once a second, sounds nice in principle to have real-time data, but in terms of data storage and the API, that's obscene to have a row per second or something is pretty crazy. I don't think it's helpful to have that resolution either. 


